<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF and Orange County Public Schools Team Up to Inspire Future IT Wizards</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Jan. 10,, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:niels@cs.ucf.edu ">Niels da Vitoria Lobo, UCF Engineering and Computer Science</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407- 823-2873 </li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004102829c5520117409af4cd007d3a"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>What if your computer crashed at work and there were no IT wizards to get it up and running again? The National Science Foundation hopes you never find out. <br />
<br />
That&rsquo;s why it launched the Information Technology Experiences for Students and Teachers program. It funds projects that teach school-age children and educators beginner knowledge of computer-based information systems &mdash; better known as IT. <br />
<br />
The latest recipients are the University of Central Florida and Orange County Public Schools, which landed a three-year, $1.2 million grant to create a program that incorporates IT skills in high-school mathematics lessons. <br />
<br />
UCF computer science professors Niels da Vitoria Lobo and Mubarak Shah, along with education professors Juli Dixon and Regina Gresham, will work with Orange County to develop the curriculum and deliver it to teachers and students. They will also show students the importance of mathematics in designing, implementing and supporting computer-based information systems, which are important to everything from medicine to entertainment.<br />
<br />
Universities all over the country are teaming up with school districts and industry to find ways to spark interest among students IT. Among other universities pursuing similar research are University of Michigan at Ann Arbor and Purdue University.<br />
<br />
UCF will implement its grant project (PROFIT, Pictures Represent Opportunities for Inspiration in Technology) in the summer.<br />
<br />
For the next three years, 20 teachers from Orange County schools will get 120 hours of professional development during a summer academy at UCF. They will also complete 40 hours of follow-up training at weekend workshops. <br />
<br />
Sixty incoming 10th-graders each year will learn about math concepts important to IT at a UCF-hosted summer institute during the next three years. During the school year, the teens will visit the university and attend quarterly social events on weekends to network with industry representatives and community leaders.<br />
<br />
It is expected that the public school teachers trained through UCF will impart the integrated math lessons to about 1,500 students by 2010.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands for Opportunit</strong>y -- Established in 1963, the University of Central Florida is a diverse metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th-largest in the country with more than 48,000 students. Located in Orlando, Fla., UCF offers high-quality undergraduate and graduate education, student development, and continuing education, while conducting cutting-edge research that powers the region&rsquo;s economic development. For more UCF news, visit http://news.ucf.edu</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
		
	
